   <title class="- topic/title " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\HB20Datasheet\XYMemoryInterfaced1e2206.xml" xtrc="title:1;3:11">XY Memory Interface</title>
   <body class="- topic/body " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\HB20Datasheet\XYMemoryInterfaced1e2206.xml" xtrc="body:1;4:10">
         

         <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\HB20Datasheet\XYMemoryInterfaced1e2206.xml" xtrc="p:1;7:13">XY memory is a feature commonly found in DSP processors to increase the DSP performance. The XY component allows the ARC-EM11D processor to implicitly load source operands and store results into a closely coupled memory (CCM) using a single instruction. This results in dense code and high performance. XY memory is accessed through a set of address pointers and modifiers in the address generation unit (AGU). Modifiers define the data type and increment values for the XY address pointers in the AGU. For the ARC-EM11D cores, X memory is often denoted as XCCM, and Y memory is often denoted as YCCM.</p>
         <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\HB20Datasheet\XYMemoryInterfaced1e2206.xml" xtrc="p:2;8:13">Using the XY memory architecture allows a single ARC-EM11D instruction to perform all the following manipulations in a single clock cycle:</p>
